/resources/791059/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-16","Shipping: North Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many vessels normally trading on routes in the North Sea oil and gas industry are owned in (a) the UK, (b) the EEA and (c) outside the EEA.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","113489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791060","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-21","<p>There are a range of people across the organisation involved with managing social media channels alongside other responsibilities but as such, the proportion of time spent on managing social media differs across these roles and teams so it is not possible to provide exact numbers.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>There are no people employed in the Department (including the Executive Agencies) on a full or part-time basis that are solely responsible for social media content or management.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791060/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T14:41:38.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791060/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791060/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-16","Department for Transport: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people in his Department with responsibility for social media are employed on a (a) full and (b) part-time basis.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","113534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791061","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-21","<p>Where we have contracts specifically for Social Media -</p><p> </p><p>2017 - £39K</p><p>2016 - £113K</p><p>2015 - £72K</p><p>2014 - £3K</p><p>2013 - £117</p><p> </p><p>In addition we hold a contract for Media Buying where Social Media may be used as part of a wider campaign. We are not able to disaggregate Social Media spend from historical data but we currently estimate to spend around £250k this year.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791061/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T10:22:15.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791061/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791061/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-16","Department for Work and Pensions: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has made an estimate of its advertising spending across social media platforms in the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","113531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791062","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-21","<p>A self employed person earning above the Minimum Income Floor but with fluctuating earnings, will receive the same amount of Universal Credit as a person with the same fluctuating earnings from employment.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791062/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T15:02:55.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791062/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791062/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-16","Universal Credit: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a self-employed claimant with fluctuating earnings, who earns more than the minimum income floor annually, receives less universal credit than an employed counterpart with the same level of annual earnings.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","113526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791063","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-21","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I gave on 13 November 2017 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-11-06/111728/" target="_blank">UIN111728</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The department is not able to reliably estimate the number of past disallowances who would benefit from this change. Therefore it is not possible to estimate how many initially unsuccessful claimants from Feltham and Heston are now eligible</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791063/answer",,,,,,"2017-11-21T13:38:53.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791063/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791063/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-16","Personal Independence Payment: Feltham and Heston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many initially unsuccessful Personal Independent Payment (PIP) claimants from Feltham and Heston are now eligible for PIP under the updated PIP guidelines.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","113492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791064","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-24","<p>The Universal Credit Scottish Flexibilities are a matter for the Scottish Government as part of the Scotland Act 2016 and this is their policy.</p><p>The Universal Credit Scottish Flexibilities, now also known as “Universal Credit Scottish choices”, have been made available from 4 October 2017 to people living in Scotland making a new Universal Credit claim, in areas where the full service is available. They allow for claimants to choose to be paid twice monthly, effectively delaying their full benefit payment by 15 days, and to choose to have the relevant housing costs in their award paid to their landlord. New claimants from 4th October have the ability to request the Scottish Choices at any point in their claim.</p><p>Claimants retain the ability to have their payments made monthly and keep control of their finances by paying their landlord themselves which we believe more effectively mirrors work, and supports claimants back into work.</p><p>It is the responsibility of the Scottish government to publicise the payment options for Universal Credit in Scotland.</p><p>Nationally, Universal Credit allows where appropriate for rent to be paid direct to landlords and for payments to be split, or for payments to be made more frequently each month.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791064/answer",,,,,"113498 ; 113501","2017-11-24T14:57:11.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791064/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/791064/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-16","Universal Credit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to allow claimants of universal credit in Scotland to request having the housing element paid directly to a social and private sector landlord at the point of their initial claim instead of after their first payment.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","113500"
